1005. Sed erus eccum ante ostium. We should expect either erum eccum or erus eccum adest (see note on v. 169). Brix changes et to est 01· st:

Sed erus eccum ante ostiumst, erus alter eccum ex Alide Rediit. But eccum is not used with the Simple Verb est, but only with adest, astat, incedit, &c., the practice being to use the other form of expression, e.g. erum eccum, in cases where the Simple Verb est would be required. Leo retains the reading of the MSS„ supposing that the Verb rediit of the second clause does duty for astat or adest in the first clause. It is at least equally probable that erum has been changed to erus in some archetype. (On the legitimate hiatus Se‘cZ emim e‘ccmn, see Introd. ii. ξ 40.) In Rud. 1174 we have something of a parallel to this line: Ego sum Daemones, et mater tua eccam (ecca MSS.) hic z‘ntvs Daedalis, where some editors change intus to intusa.

1006. Salue. Fleckeisen proposed salveto, which however is never found at the beginning of a clause (cf. liud. 103 pater, salueto, 416 salue, adulescens). Spengel's O salue is a preferable way of removing the hiatus (cf. Men. 1132 O salue, insperate...fi-ater). But it is quite conceivable that a pause followed salue (Introd. ii. ξ 44). Gnate mi (cf. 1021).
